                        "type": "1",
                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "A client with hyperthyroidism has been given methimazole. Which nursing considerations are associated with this medication? Select all that apply.",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nCommon side effects of methimazole include nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea. To address these side effects, this medication needs to be taken with food. Because of the increase in metabolism that occurs in hyperthyroidism, the client needs to consume a high-calorie diet. Antithyroid medications can cause agranulocytosis with leukopenia and thrombocytopenia. Sore throat, fever, headache, or bleeding may indicate agranulocytosis, and the primary health care provider needs to be notified immediately. Methimazole is not radioactive and would not be stopped abruptly, due to the risk of thyroid storm.\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nFocus on the subject, nursing considerations for administering methimazole. Focus on the client's diagnosis. Think about the pathophysiology associated with the diagnosis and the medication and the actions and effects of antithyroid medications to assist in answering correctly.",
                        "id": "69706d0168d84d3d8f8bcceb0e37015f",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    }
                ]
            },
